The portal is designed for conducting mass health screening camps at schools. It brings together three main groups of stakeholders: Admins, School Point of Contacts (POCs), and Medical Specialists.

Here is a comprehensive breakdown of the platform.

Part 1: Detailed Functionalities (By Role)
1. Admin Area
The Admin is the superuser who sets up the system, registers other users, and creates the medical camps.

User Management (Registration):
Register School POCs (along with their school details like name, address, phone). The system generates a username and a temporary password.
Register Medical Specialists by selecting their specific role/department (e.g., Community Medicine, Dental, ENT, Eye, Skin, Other).
Camp/Event Management:
Schedule new health screening camps. This involves selecting a registered School, setting Start/End dates, and defining operational hours.
View all camps categorized dynamically into "Upcoming," "Ongoing," and "Completed."
Dashboard & Analytics:
View high-level statistics like Total Students Screened, Number of Active Doctors, Number of Schools registered, etc.
2. School POC Area
The School POC represents a school where a camp is being held. They manage the student roster and track the screening progress.

Student Roster & Tracking:
View camps assigned to their school.
Add Students: Manually add students one-by-one or use a Bulk CSV Upload feature for an entire classroom.
Generate QR Codes for each student, which doctors will later scan.
Mark students as Absent if they don't show up to the camp.
Insights & Result Management:
View live statistics of the camp: how many students are Normal, under Observation, require Referral, or are Absent.
Bulk Print / Download Prescriptions: Print out the finalized health reports and prescriptions for students based on applied filters.
3. Medical Specialists Workflow
Medical Specialists consist of doctors from various departments who examine the students during the camp.

Volunteer System:
Doctors are not strictly assigned; they log in, view a directory of "Active Camps," and click Volunteer to join a camp for the day.
Student Screening (Exam Workspace):
Search for a student manually by typing details or by scanning their QR Code.
General Assessment: Typically, a Community Medicine doctor or nursing staff will fill out a General Info Form (Height, Weight, BMI calculation, basic symptoms).
Specialized Assessment: Each doctor views a form customized to their specialty (e.g., Dental, ENT). They record their findings and flag the child's status as either Normal, Observation, or Referral.
History & Sync: The system works offline-first for smooth fieldwork and syncs data to the server when an internet connection is available.
Part 2: Prerequisites Before Testing
Before you begin executing your test scripts, ensure the following is set up:

Application Running: Ensure the frontend and backend (React + Python/Flask) are running.
Database Initialized: An empty database initializes itself with one default Admin account.
Default Admin Username: Admin
Default Admin Password: admin (Note: The system might prompt the admin to set up a new password upon first login, depending on the OTP/Auth flow setup).
Email Deliverability (Optional but Recommended): The platform uses an OTP (One-Time Password) system for login. If you don't have access to the email accounts being registered, ensure you note down the generated passwords shown on the screen when the Admin creates the users so you can use the "Password Fallback" login option.
Part 3: Proper Workflow & Step-by-Step Testing Order
To simulate a real-world scenario, you must follow the chronological flow of setting up a camp. Do not attempt to test the Doctor or School POC workflow before the Admin has completed the setup.

Here is the exact order to test the system:

Step 1: Admin Setup & Onboarding
Login as Admin: Go to the login screen and log in using the default Admin credentials.
Register a School POC: Navigate to User Registration. Register a "School POC" (e.g., "Delhi Public School"). Important: Save the generated username and password shown on the success screen!
Register Doctors: Register at least two different specialists (e.g., one Community Medicine doctor and one Dental doctor). Save their generated credentials.
Create a Camp (Event): Go to Camp Management. Create a new event assigned to the school you just created. Ensure the dates cover "Today" so it shows up as an Ongoing camp.
Log out.
Step 2: School POC Preparations
Login as the School POC: Use the credentials generated in Step 1. You may be asked to set up a permanent password if it's your first time.
View Camp: Navigate to your dashboard and verify that the camp created by the Admin appears here.
Add Students: Go to Manage Students. Add a few test students manually (e.g., "John Doe", "Jane Smith"). Also, try the Bulk CSV upload if you are testing edge cases.
Mark Absent (Edge Case): Pick one student and mark them as Absent.
Generate QR Codes: Test printing/downloading the QR codes for the students.
Log out.
Step 3: Medical Specialist Field Work
Login as Community Medicine Doctor: Use the credentials from Step 1.
Volunteer: View the Active Camps directory and click "Volunteer" for the created camp.
Examine a Student: Search for "John Doe" (or scan the text of his QR code). Complete the General Info Form (Height, Weight, etc.) and save it.
Log out.
Login as Dental Doctor: Use the other credentials from Step 1.
Volunteer & Examine: Volunteer for the same camp. Search for "John Doe". Notice that the General Info is already filled. Now, fill out the specific Dental assessment form. Mark this student as needing a Referral.
Log out.
Step 4: Final Validation (Close the loop)
Login as the School POC again.
Check Progress: Go to the Progress Tracking tab. Ensure the statistics update correctly (e.g., 1 Referral, 1 Absent).
Print Prescription: Select "John Doe" and verify that you can download/print a prescription containing the consolidated findings of both doctors.
Following this exact sequence ensures that the relational data dependencies (School -> Camp -> Students -> Health Records) are perfectly met, allowing you to thoroughly test every corner of the application without running into validation blocks!